    <Node ToolID="436">
      <GuiSettings Plugin="AlteryxGuiToolkit.TextBox.TextBox">
        <Position x="755.1" y="57" width="314" height="720" />
      </GuiSettings>
      <Properties>
        <Configuration>
          <Text>Pie Wedge Trade Area

This macro constructs trade areas around stores consisting of "pie wedges" whose extent depends on the distribution of customers around the store.

There are two Inputs:
"Stores" requires two fields:
   -- "Key" is a unique identifier for the store
   --"SpatialObj" is  a point with the store location
 
"Customers" specifies three fields:
   -- "Key" matches the Stores input and specifies which store theis customer is associated with
  -- "SpatialObj" is a point with the customers location
  -- "Weight" is a numeric field indicating the relative significance of this customer


The macro works on each store (and its associated set of  customers) individually.  The customers will be assigned to wdges based on their direction from the store; some percentage of outlying customers will be dropped, and polygons will be constructed fro the wedges containing the remaining customers.  This is controlled by four configuration elements:

-- Numberof Wedges: sets the number of wedges around each store location.  
-- Oversample multiplier: Having a lot of customers close too, but just to one side of a wedge boundary can cause the resulting trade areas to be unreasonably spiky.  One way to correct this is with the "oversample" multiplier.  Setting this above 1 will effectively make each wedge wider by this fraction, so the sample areas of adjacent wedges will overlap and be less sensitive to such edge effects.  It is probably unreasonable to set this under 1 or over 2.
--Fraction of outliers to drop:  To arrive at a core trade area, the macro will drop this fraction of outliers (adjusted by weight).  The total amount of "weight" to drop will be calculated, and split evenly between wedges.  After this many of the furthest customers have been removed, the wedge polygon wil be generated extending to the furthest remaining customer.
--Buffer results:  Finally, the macro offers the ability to optionally buffer the resulting polygons.  this will round off the otherwise sharp-cornered polygons considerably.  Also, the macro uses a two-step process, apply a buffer twice the size specified, followed by a negative buffer of the size specified.  This results in an aproprtiate buffer, but preferentially fills in the narrow gaps the process is prone to.</Text>
          <Font name="Microsoft Sans Serif" size="8.25" style="0" />
          <TextColor name="Black" />
          <FillColor name="White" />
          <Shape shape="0" />
          <Justification Justification="0" />
        </Configuration>
        <Annotation DisplayMode="0">
          <Name>TextBox (436)</Name>
          <DefaultAnnotationText />
          <Left value="False" />
        </Annotation>
      </Properties>
    </Node>
